feedback: I liked that it was able to answer all the questions I had. Additionally, I liked that it highlights part of the code in the text. I would like to see a short answer first and the option for more explanation.

I liked that it was able to adjust the length of the answer based on the question. The explanations were clear to me. Although it seemed better to fit the length of the answer to the question, I still would like an option for more information. For example, this response could have been "Yes it returns a string with the current working directory" But the answer the chatbot gave was: "Yes, that's correct! In the code snippet provided, os.getcwd() is used to get the current working directory (cwd) path. This function returns a string representing the current working directory where the Python script is being executed.". Although this is context dependent.
speed_feedback: Maybe there was a slight difference, but it was not big enough for me to be affected by it. However it could be a problem if I give it more information to process, I don't know.

feedback: I liked that it responded with a thourough answer, which also included the code snippet, even if you did not ask question about the code snippet directly
Also liked how the chatbot included the code snippet even when the question was not explicitly related to the code snippet.
speed_feedback: At the first chatbot the first question I asked I noticed that it took some time, after that I did not notice/paid attention to any other response times.

feedback:
Thorough answers with a lot of details, also about the code that is used before and after the line I asked questions about. The language of the chatbot was clear and understandable.

There were no aspects I did not like. I can imagine it would be a harder task would I have never seen code in my life.

I liked the thorough explanations and the clear summaries about the snippets of code.

I did not really like the encouragement "feel free to ask", as this was repetatively done. In the end it was kind of annoying. The chatbot sometimes provided more general information than the other chatbot about the functioning of code. I more liked the practical knowledge of chatbot A in this case.
speed_feedback: No, it did not matter to me.

feedback:
I could ask it pretty complex questions that requires understanding of the entire code (what effect does the TF-TDF score have on the final output in `comparisons`? and what can this code be used for?) and it was able to give an answer that was applicable to the code.
It does tend to give quite long answers though. For the question about the effect of the TF-IDF score, it gave a bit too much background information for me, so it takes unnecessarily long to read.

This chatbot gives much shorter answers than chatbot A, but always formats its answers as a single paragraph without any emphasis / bold parts. I actually prefer the longer (but formatted) answers of chatbot A.
It seems to give quite general answers that do not necessarily directly relate to this program, even when asked to be more specific to this program (it just repeated its previous answer just worded slightly differently). It also added fluff at the end of its last answers ("if you have more questions, feel free to ask"), which is useless.
It was able to explain how the plot would end up looking, which is nice, though it was not very to the point.
speed_feedback: Not much, but I noticed for chatbot B that I continued looking through the code for a bit after I had asked a question, instead of waiting for it to answer.

feedback: It feels like Chatbot A tends to give too much information, which is an issue when I'm on a time limit. Chatbot A seems to understand what I'm trying to say fortunately.

Like Chatbot A, it gives too much information. Aside from it being slightly slower, I feel as though the 2 chatbots are identical. Since they were used for different questions, I don't know when their responses would be different.
speed_feedback: While I didn't notice it initially, after doing the questions, I realized I had more to ask Chatbot b than I did with the given time.

feedback:
I liked that Chatbot A immediately gave me the answers I needed, without needing to clarify myself further. It also understood library code without me needing to explain which library the methods were from.

I disliked (but only slightly) that some of the answers Chatbot A gave were longer than I feel like they needed to be, but it might be useful for someone else to have detailed answers.

I liked that Chatbot B gave more concise answers than Chatbot A. This did result in me having to ask for clarification 2-3 times, but this was not necessarily annoying. The answers Chatbot B gave me usually explained enough to understand what I wanted to understand. I think I asked a few more questions in this task than the previous because I was less familiar with the methods used, not because Chatbot B gave worse answers.
speed_feedback:
The first response from Chatbot A took a longer time than I expected. This made me think for a few seconds that it was broken. Chatbot B sometimes surprised me by how quickly it responded, which I found interesting.
I think otherwise the difference in response time did not cause frustration with either bot. They are both pretty quick, and as long as the answers don't take as long as that first answer in Chatbot A (I think 5 seconds???) I would mostly look at the type of answers they give.

feedback: I liked that the chatbot gave extensive answers. Sometimes I did not understand what the terms meant that were used (e.g. tuple, array)

speed_feedback: it took a little bit longer and I felt a little rushed so sometimes it would have been nice if it responded a little bit faster. but that wasn't significantly affecting my results I think

feedback: Chatbot A gave very clear and extensive answers to my questions. For now I don't have any negative remarks.

Chatbot B also gave extensive answers to my questions, also when I did not give the specific code yet. I liked the fact that it gave me a summary of the answer to the questions. But I don't remember if chatbot A did that as well.
speed_feedback: No, I found both chatbots quite fast.

feedback: it could easily connect my question to the given code and explain it to me, even when the question wasn't the best
it connected my questions well to the code given and gave an easy to understand and clear answer that helped understand the code.
speed_feedback: no, neither took long enough to be a bother

feedback: It was very straightforward to use and with very little input provided exactly the information I was looking for.

Just like A, it responded very well to my inputs and gave very complete information. I did notice, however, that the answers are sometimes structured differently. feedback: Generally, I thought that the chatbot gave me much needed context for the code. My expertise in writing and reading code is low so the chatbot gave the opportunity to clearify needed shortcomings in my abilities.
It understands things on the surface but when you ask a question based on an educated guess it has to inputed your thinking to get to the same conclusion.
speed_feedback: It didn't effect me that much because I kept reading the code while it was busy so I am not that sure if it was faster or slower.
